Migration, the seven Rs.

Most A-W-S customers do not arrive in greenfield. They arrive with a data centre, a portfolio of workloads, and a deadline. Migration is the discipline of moving from there to here without breaking the business in transit, and the framing A-W-S pushes, popularised by Gartner, is the seven Rs. Every workload is being one of seven things.

Retire means turn it off, for a workload that's unused or duplicated. Retain means leave it on-premises for now, when latency, compliance, or vendor lock-in makes the move uneconomic. Rehost is lift-and-shift to E-C-2, the fastest move with minimal change, the forklift to the cloud. Relocate is specifically moving VMware workloads to VMware Cloud on A-W-S. Replatform is lift-and-tinker, small optimisations on the way, like moving a database to R-D-S, for modest gains without an application rewrite. Repurchase is replacing the workload with S-A-A-S, dropping a licensed C-R-M and buying Salesforce, when a S-A-A-S equivalent exists. And Refactor is rebuilding for the cloud, breaking a monolith into microservices or going serverless, the highest value but the highest effort and longest timeline.

Picking the R is half the migration; the service that moves the bytes is the other half. The practical sequencing most enterprises follow is: Retire and Retain first to cut the scope you don't move, then Rehost the majority to get out of the data centre fast, then Replatform and Refactor over time as workloads earn the investment. Trying to Refactor everything up front is the classic way to miss the deadline; get to the cloud first, and modernise once you're there.
